= Addressing Our Economic Crisis

Our moribund party is predictably wracked as to how to deal with the economic crisis. From the passivist faction, Hilferding argues that the economic crisis must be allowed to play out, ostensibly because it is simply a part of the cyclic nature of capitalism, and also because this approach would allow the SPD to orchestrate the famine and mass death of the working class without lifting a finger. 

From trade union class traitors, a failed ex-Menshevik named Wladimir Woytinsky argues that we must pursue a massive public works program to reduce unemployment and stimulate demand, perhaps including deficit spending. This so-called WTB plan, named after its chief supporters Woytinsky, Tarnow, and Baade, is certain to cause a return to hyper-inflation without helping the economy, and is directly opposed to Marxist principles. For these reasons, it is receiving a lot of positive attention within the party.

However, liberals in the party argue that the WTB plan is merely a bandage over the fundamental flaws of capitalism. They appropriate KPD rhetoric to argue that the crisis is an opportunity to end capitalism through massive nationalizations of industry, and finally bring our country to socialism.

Meanwhile, capitalist lackeys and Nazi infiltrators draw up proposals for a limited plan of capitulation through public works, funded through taxes on the poor, that does not involve inconveniencing their corporate overlords. Even the self-serving union cliques realize that such plan is inadequate in its scale and goals.

