Woytinsky and his trade union cronies vehemently criticize our paralyzed leadership for this policy. The workers are starving; are we going to callously abandon them and side with bourgeois austerity? Why yes, of course we are. On the other hand, the passivists criticize Woytinsky for promising the workers false hope; their position is that better things are impossible. 

Our policy course is, as always, that nothing can be done to alleviate the depression and we shouldn't even try.


